			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Procedural level generation tends to need more RAM than hardcoded levels, and RAM is one thing that the NES doesn't have much of. The exception is one-way scrolling like that of <em>Super Mario Bros.</em>, where the procedural level generator could conceivably replace the level decompression code. But even in that case, balancing procedural levels to ensure even difficulty progression was not trivial.<br /><br />One pre-NES example: <em>River Raid</em> for Atari 2600 is procedural with a fixed seed as a compression technique.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

